 $5,000 favorable.\"", "\"OVERALL MATERIAL VARIANCE\":\"Overall material variance is the sum of price variance and usage variance. In this case, it is $43,000 adverse + $5,000 favorable = $38,000 adverse.\"", "\"QUIZ: LEARNING CURVES AND VARIANCES\":\"This quiz involves calculating traditional labor rate and efficiency variances, and re-calculating them considering the learning curve effect.\"", "\"RE-CALCULATED LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\":\"Re-calculated labour efficiency variance = Actual labour hours * Standard rate - Standard hours for actual production (taking into account the learning rate) * Standard rate\"", "\"MARKET SIZE VARIANCE\":\"Market size variance\" is a financial metric used to measure the difference between actual and expected market performance. It can be calculated using several formulas. One method is: (Actual market size * Budgeted market share - Budgeted sales quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Another approach is: (Revised sales volume - Budget sales volume) * Standard contribution. A third formula is: (Original budget quantity - Revised standard quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Each of these methods provides a way to assess the impact of market size changes on profitability.", "\"MARKET SHARE VARIANCE\":\"Market share variance (sales volume operational variance) measures the difference between the actual sales volume and the revised budgeted sales volume, based on the actual market size. It helps in understanding the impact of market share changes on sales volume. The formula for calculating market share variance is: (Actual sales quantity - Revised budgeted quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Alternatively, it can also be expressed as (Actual sales volume - revised sales volume) * standard contribution. Essentially, market share variance is the difference between the actual sales and the budgeted market share of the actual market. For instance, in a quiz scenario involving Riley Co, the market share variance would be calculated by considering the actual market size and sales achieved compared to the budgeted market share and sales.\"", "\"SALES PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the traditional sales volume variance, market size variance, and market share variance for Acme based on given sales data.\"", "\"ADVANTAGES AND DISADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Advantages include distinguishing between variances caused by planning or operating factors and providing feedback control. Disadvantages are not provided in the text.\"", "\"STANDARD LABOUR COST\":The \"STANDARD LABOUR COST\" was calculated as 2 hours of labor at a rate of $10 per hour.", "\"ADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Advantages of variance analysis include distinguishing between variances caused by bad planning or unavoidable factors and those resulting from operating factors, providing feedback control on processes needing correction, updating standards to current conditions, and improving motivation by assessing managers only on variances under their control.\"", "\"DISADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Disadvantages of variance analysis include extra data requirements, being time-consuming, potential manipulation by managers claiming external causes for adverse variances and internal causes for favorable variances, and operational managers blaming poor standard setting for adverse variances.\"", "\"MANIPULATION OF BUDGETS AND STANDARDS\":\"Manipulation of budgets and standards refers to the revision of budgets and standards at the end of the year to hide adverse variances, which should be prevented by strict rules and independent, verifiable evidence.\"", "\"EFFECT ON STAFF MOTIVATION AND ACTION\":\"Effect on staff motivation and action refers to how variance analysis and standard costing can impact the motivation of managers and staff, potentially leading to morale issues if used insensitively, and causing employees to conceal adverse variances or take actions that may not be in the company's best interests.\"", "\"PERFORMANCE EVALUATION USING VARIANCES\":\"Performance evaluation using variances involves using variance analysis to assess the performance of managers and staff, identifying the causes of variances, and determining who is responsible for them.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}